Principal Component Analysis

Dataset water.zostera.LUSI.red.scaled

This dataset contains 28 individuals and 9 variables, 1 qualitative variable is considered as illustrative.

1. Inertia distribution

The inertia of the first dimensions shows if there are strong relationships between variables and suggests the number of dimensions that should be studied.

The first two dimensions of PCA express 56.73% of the total dataset inertia ; that means that 56.73% of the individuals (or variables) cloud total variability is explained by the plane. This percentage is relatively high and thus the first plane well represents the data variability. This value is greater than the reference value that equals 50.27%, the variability explained by this plane is thus significant (the reference value is the 0.95-quantile of the inertia percentages distribution obtained by simulating 858 data tables of equivalent size on the basis of a normal distribution).

From these observations, it should be better to also interpret the dimensions greater or equal to the third one.

Figure 1 - Decomposition of the total inertia on the components of the PCA

An estimation of the right number of axis to interpret suggests to restrict the analysis to the description of the first 3 axis. These axis present an amount of inertia greater than those obtained by the 0.95-quantile of random distributions (76.59% against 65.8%). This observation suggests that only these axis are carrying a real information. As a consequence, the description will stand to these axis.

Figure 2.4 - Qualitative factor map (PCA) The labeled factors are those the best shown on the plane.

The dimension 1 opposes individuals such as 1, 5, 10 and 3 (to the right of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals such as 21, 19 and 14 (to the left of the graph, characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis).

The group in which the individuals 1, 5, 10 and 3 stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables chl_a, PO4, LUSI and seston (variables are sorted from the strongest).

The group in which the individuals 21, 19 and 14 stand (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • low values for the variables LUSI, Ntotal and NH4 (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The dimension 2 opposes individuals such as 7, 2, 26 and 18 (to the top of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals such as 21, 19 and 14 (to the bottom of the graph, characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis).

The group in which the individuals 7, 2, 26 and 18 stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables Ntotal and NO3 (variables are sorted from the strongest).

The group in which the individuals 21, 19 and 14 stand (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • low values for the variables LUSI, Ntotal and NH4 (variables are sorted from the weakest).

4. Classification

Figure 4 - Ascending Hierarchical Classification of the individuals. The classification made on individuals reveals 3 clusters.

The cluster 1 is made of individuals such as 11, 14, 19, 21 and 26. This group is characterized by :

  • low values for the variables LUSI and chl_a (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The cluster 2 is made of individuals such as 2, 7 and 18. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables LUSI, Ntotal and NO3 (variables are sorted from the strongest).

The cluster 3 is made of individuals such as 1, 3, 5 and 10. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables chl_a and PO4 (variables are sorted from the strongest).
